The problem is probably caused by the API running on a different port. See https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19966707/cors-error-on-same-domain

Try adding `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` and `Access-Control-Allow-Methods` headers to your API.

This is how this is achieved on [Express][1] using [middleware][2].

The following allows all origins and methods (this might be too open depending on your requirements).

```javascript
const express = require(&#39;express&#39;);
const app = express();
const port = 3000;

app.use((req, res, next) =&gt; {
  res.header(&#39;Access-Control-Allow-Origin&#39;, &#39;*&#39;);
  res.header(&#39;Access-Control-Allow-Methods&#39;, &#39;*&#39;);
  next();
});

app.get(&#39;/&#39;, (req, res) =&gt; res.send(&#39;Hello World!&#39;));

app.listen(port, () =&gt; console.log(`Example app listening on port ${port}!`));
```


  [1]: https://expressjs.com/
  [2]: https://expressjs.com/en/guide/using-middleware.html

